<font color="#FF0000">ONE VET'S APPROACH </font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan 13 23:56:58 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I have been going into Philadelphia public and parochial high schools both with and without other Vietnam Vets. The first thing I usually must do is counteract the impression left by Hollywood that we all are crazed druggies. In the inner city public schools, I have to work hard to keep the class awake. With the lengthy snow emergency last winter, I only got into one school in 1996. It's getting harder to find history/social studies departments that will make the time for a Vietnam Vet to come in, including my sons' alma mater.         <br>
 <br>
I try hard to give a balanced picture of the conflict plus the geographical, historical and cultural background. I keep up on the literature from &quot;Fire In The Lake&quot; to &quot;Bloods&quot; to &quot;We Were Soldiers Once And Young&quot; to &quot;A Historical Atlas Of The Vietnam War&quot; to &quot;A Rumor Of War&quot;. As I said some days ago in the &quot;Vet/Non-Vet dialog&quot; section; We were neither the bad guys nor quite the good guys. South Vietnam was created largely at our insistence at Geneva. The US was not about to have a Communist leaning government control all of Vietnam. The Southerners had very little say. Diem was a transplanted Northern Catholic with no real base outside the 900,000 Catholics that fled the North. This does not excuse the execreble methods the Communists used during and after the war. As for us, we totally ignored the basics such as &quot;Know Your Enemy&quot; and &quot;What Is The Probable Cost To Win And Will We Pay It?&quot;. I believe both that we made a mistake going in, dozens of mistakes in prosecuting the war, and then swung too far the other way with the total abandonment of the South. In a thousand ways the Vietnam War still exacts a price on the heart and soul of this nation, spiritually, culturally and economically. Those who say the ghost of Vietnam has been exorcised from our foreign policy haven't been listening to the public debate on our role in the world and how to perform it.<br><br>
How do I get all this into a 50 minute period?...I don't! After 10 to 15 minutes of intro, I go where the questions take me, and pray I've done some good. 
